1.	Implementation experience or relation:
QA experience of functional testing, configured system, delivered training to team members. Especially experience of working with Controcc, financial imports and exports
2.	How to gather and validate requirements?
I start with stakeholder interviews and process mapping to understand the current state. Then I run workshops to define future state requirements and use prototypes to validate assumptions before sign off.
3.	Handle a difficult client or stakeholder
A stakeholder disagreed with the proposed workflow. I scheduled a focused session, listened to their concerns, demonstrated the impact using data, and we aligned on a revised solution that met both compliance and usability needs
4.	How to approach testing during implementation
I create test cases mapped to requirements, run SIT to validate configuration, support users during UAT, and manage defects through a structured triage process.
5.	How to ensure a successful go-live
I prepare a detailed cutover plan, validate migrated data, ensure users are trained, and set up hyper care support. Clear communication is key to reducing go live anxiety.
6.	What to do when client asks for something impossible or out of scope
I explain the limitation in business terms, outline risks, and propose feasible alternatives. If it’s out of scope, I document it and discuss change control options
7.	How to manage priorities and tight deadlines
I prioritize based on impact and urgency, communicate early with stakeholders, and break work into manageable tasks
8.	Why you want to be an implementation consultant
I’ve spent many years as a QA engineer, and while I’ve learned a lot from that experience, I’m ready to step out of my comfort zone and take on a more client facing role. I enjoy understanding how people use technology, and I want to be closer to the business side where I can help clients translate their needs into real solutions.
My background in software testing gives me a strong foundation in problem solving, system thinking, and quality assurance — all of which are valuable during implementations. At the same time, I’m excited about the opportunity to build new skills, especially around stakeholder communication, solution design, and project delivery.
Becoming an implementation consultant feels like the right next step because it lets me leverage what I already do well while challenging myself to grow in areas that matter to me professionally

